    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-24T11:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-24T11:41:00-05:00" n="548"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d548">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/488</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-24T18:00:00+01:19">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 24, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 25, 2.58 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2881. Your 1254, May 22, 6 p.m., received today.<note n="2" xml:id="d548fn2">Not
                        printed.</note> Press despatch as quoted by you gives a correct statement.
                    It is announced that the convoy will sail on June 5, composed of <hi
                        rend="italic">Hertog Hendrik</hi>, the auxiliary <pb facs="0661" n="1495"
                        xml:id="pg_1495"/> cruiser <hi rend="italic">Tabanan</hi> and the steamship
                        <hi rend="italic">Noordam</hi>. The convoy is said to be bound for
                    Netherlands India [<hi rend="italic">Indies</hi>] with enough coal to carry
                    through without entering foreign ports. The British Minister tells me that he
                    has formally protested by instruction of his Government against the sailing of
                    the convoy, informing the Dutch Government that Great Britain would not
                    recognize it but would exercise the right of search on the high seas if
                    necessary. He adds that <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1"
                        >Loudon</persName> told him that he had telegraphed the Dutch Minister at
                    London in regard to the whole matter. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TSWB1">Townley</persName> says he does not know
                    the nature of this telegram but, as it went a week or more ago and no further
                    word has come from his Government, he supposes it must have been
                    satisfactory.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
